For many years there was a wonderful restaurant in Point Arena, CA called Panegea. One of their best dishes was salmon with horseradish sauce. I approximated it at home with horseradish and mayo. But this sauce was even better. I read elsewhere that salmon and basil have the same affinity as salmon and horseradish and it's true. I used almost all of my fresh basil in the salad accompanying the salmon, and with the full amount or even more, the sauce would be even better. I cooked the salmon in a fish basket at my husband's suggestion, but next time I'll omit the basket. It was more trouble than it was worth. Mine didn't come out at brown as the photo, but since the pieces were no more than 1 inch thick, they were perfect in the time recommended. I didn't see the comments about marinading until later but I would definitely double the mop sauce and marinading it is a great idea. With it I served the Barefoot Contessa's Panzanella Salad (tomatoes, bell peppers, onions, and basil) from her Parties book. Some garlic bread. An absoslutely perfect summer meal. We bought Costco's fresh Alaskan Copper River salmon from their fish cart. I'm not sure about using farmed salmon (which we try to avoid if possible). In a pinch I think you could use the frozen salmon patties from Costco also. That means you could have this on short notice and regardless of your access to fresh salmon. In summary: the best recipe for grilled salmon yet!

